==English==
===Etymology===
Shortened from '''[[Pakistani]]'''

===Proper noun===
'''Paki''' (''plural'' '''Pakis''')

#(''derogatory, offensive and racist'') A [[Pakistani]], or, more generally, a person of who is perceived to be a Pakistani; often applied to persons of any South Asian or Middle Eastern origin.

===Proper adjective===
'''Paki''' (''no [[comparative]] or [[superlative]]'')

#(''derogatory, offensive and racist when spoken by non-Pakistanis'') [[Pakistani]], or perceived to be Pakistani.

====Usage notes====
'''Paki''' became offensive during the 1960s when used by British tabloids to refer to immigrants in a derogotary and racist manner. In recent times there has been a trend by second- and third-generation British Pakistanis to reclaim the word, such as in the name of the clothing company PAK1 or the activist website [http://paki.tv paki.tv]

However the racist connotations may be confined only to the UK. In Australia, the Pakistani cricket team are commonly referred to as the Pakis, just as the West Indians are known as the Windies. Neither term is used pejoratively, and Aussies visiting the UK are generally mystified when their discussion of the cricket elicits accusations of racism.  

